  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "HF",
    "text": "The picture was sent to me-- the enlargement of this picture was sent to me from my brother from Belgium who received this to-- as a prison-- Polish prisoner of war in Germany. This is a picture of mine taken in 1941, for ID, for-- for ID identification card in Warsaw, Poland, at the age of 17. My name is Henry Frankel, spelled F-R-A-N-K-E-L, which was changed by legally obtaining naturalization papers in 1955 in the United States from the-- from the name Frenkiel, spelled F-R-E-N-K-I-E-L. I was born on June 16, 1924, in Lodz, Poland. This picture was sent to me from my brother who received this from Warsaw Ghetto in 1941, and prevailed and sent it to me at the-- on the special occasion of our reunion. This is a picture of my brother, which I received shortly after we met after the war. His name is Michael Frenkiel, Mieczyslaw, spelled M-I-E-C-Z-Y-S-L-A-W, Frenkiel. He prevailed with the name Frenkiel, spelled F-R-E-N-K-I-E-L. He was born January 26, 1918, in Warsaw, Poland. He migrate-- he was sent by my father to study textile engineering in Verviers, Belgium. And he finished his school after the war. During the war, he survived as a Polish prisoner of war in Germany under the auspices of the Swiss Red Cross. The camp was saved from any atrocities. And we met after the war. He is residing today in Belgium. And we're in constant contact. This is a picture of my brother and his wife standing at the graveside of my father, which I found in 1993 coming to the 50 anniversary of Warsaw Ghetto uprising. And accidentally walking in the Jewish Community Center in Lodz, and of being notified that the remnants of my father's body resting place is in Jewish cemetery. In 1994, I returned to Poland and decided to put up a stone in memory. And this year, of-- in May of 1996, I returned with my brother and sister-in-law to pay final respects to my father. These are photostatic copies of the letters received by my brother from the Warsaw Ghetto the war. And if I'm not mistaking, they were-- were sent in 1941 and 1940 to his camp in Germany. [SIGHS] This is copy of a letter that my-- our mutual friend [INAUDIBLE] Chodwski, spelled C-H-O-D-W-S-K-I, living very close to the headquarter of the Gestapo, sent to my brother informing him that he had seen me for the last time in early stages of 1942 prior of my departure for Majdanek.",
    "start_ms": 118285,
    "end_ms": 396915,
